“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, which does not have access to the sea, hopes that the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
The sailors are patrolling at the Navy headquarters in La Paz.
There are navy blue flags on public buildings.
The maritime bases from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon are covered with the slogan: “We have the right to the sea.
It’s our duty to get it back.”
In mainland Bolivia, the memory of the loss of the coast in a bloody dispute over natural resources with Chile in the 19th century is still alive - just like the yearning to refloat the Pacific Ocean.
This hope is perhaps the greatest after decades, as Bolivia awaits the decision of the international court, which will receive it on October 1 after five years of consultations.
“Bolivia has momentum, a spirit of unity and impartiality and, of course, in a positive spirit, awaits the result,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will look at the decision of the international court on large screens across the country and hope that the court in The Hague will rule in favor of Bolivia, which claims that after decades of volatile talks, Chile must negotiate Bolivia's access to sovereign access to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president facing a controversial re-election battle next year, also has high expectations for Monday’s verdict.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific,” he promised at the end of August.
But some analysts believe the court won't rule in Bolivia's favor -- and even if it did, it wouldn't change much.
The UN body based in the Netherlands has no authority to grant Bolivia Chilean territory and will not decide on the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the ICJ ruling comes just six months after hearing the closing arguments means that the case “wasn’t complicated,” said Paz Zirate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And the last four years are not talking in favor of Bolivia, but they may cost it a lot.
“The current Bolivian government has taken advantage of the issue of access to the sea,” said Zaratej.
Morales’ aggressive rhetoric sucked all the goodwill out of the Chileans that might still be there, she explained.
The talks between Bolivia and Chile will continue at some point, but after that it will be extremely difficult to take part in the discussions.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Veltzé, the Bolivian representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court had made an unusually quick decision.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity for a new era of relations with Chile” and the opportunity to “end 139 years of mutually beneficial disagreements,” he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales - still one of Latin America's most popular presidents - used the maritime issue as a political foothold.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific,” he added.
“Deciding is an opportunity to see that we have to overcome the past.”
