John Edward: language skills are key for global citizens
Scottish independent schools enjoy a reputation for academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exam scores, further enhanced by individual and collective successes in sport, the arts, music and other community endeavours.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service for their students and their parents.
Independent schools want to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen career path and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a customized school curriculum, we see that modern languages are still a popular and desired elective in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you talk to a person in a language that he understands, the conversation is imprinted on his memory.
But if you speak to a person in his mother tongue, the words are imprinted on his heart.”
This is a good reminder that we should not rely solely on English when we want to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s results from recent exams show that languages top the rankings with the highest success rates in independent schools.
Sixty-eight percent of students who learned a foreign language scored excellent.
Data collected in 74 Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS) member schools showed that 72% of pupils achieved an excellent grade in Mandarin and 72% of pupils in German, 69% in French and 63% in Spanish.
This proves that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as the key knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are treated as optional subjects in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere in the same way as subjects in the fields of natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Training Commission found that 17 per cent of the reasons why employers struggle to fill vacancies can be attributed to a lack of language skills.
Knowledge of languages is therefore becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future careers.
For future job opportunities that require language skills, these skills are essential in the global world.
If a person learns another language, whatever career path he chooses, with such lifelong knowledge, he has a great advantage in the future.
A multilingual person who can communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically takes precedence over the competition.
A 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK found that 75 percent of people did not speak a foreign language well enough to talk, with French being the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of respondents, that is 15 percent.
Therefore, investing in language learning is important for today’s children.
By knowing several languages, especially those from developing countries, children have a better chance of finding suitable employment.
In Scotland, schools differ in the languages they teach.
Many schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be the most important for the UK in 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of the interests of your child, it will always be possible to choose a number of languages taught by specialists in this field in independent schools.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that equips and equips children with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
In the global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages remain extremely important for the future of the country, so this must also be expressed in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
