North Korea: “Without confidence, we will not unilaterally disarm”
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued implementation of sanctions is causing growing mistrust in the United States and that under such conditions, North Korea will certainly not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Jong Ho told the World Body’s annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken a number of “significant goodwill measures” over the past year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, undermining the city for nuclear tests, and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and technology.
“But we don’t see the right response from the United States,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, we will not be confident in national security, and under such conditions we will by no means be the first to unilaterally disarm.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a gradual approach to nuclear disarmament that would reward North Korea for taking gradual measures, his statement was significant because he did not immediately reject unilateral nuclear disarmament, as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump from the first summit between the current U.S. president and the North Korean leader, held on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim pledged to pursue “nuclear disarmament of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised security assurances to North Korea.
North Korea wants an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington also did not give in to calls to release the tough international sanctions that apply to North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that we must first disarm ourselves nuclear, increases pressure with sanctions to achieve our goals by coercion, and even objects to the declaration of an end to the war,” Ri said.
“The thought that sanctions could bring us to our knees is an unrealistic hope for people who don’t even know us.
The problem is that the continued implementation of sanctions deepens our mistrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US president outlined at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean President Moon Jae-in that had taken place over the past five months, adding: “If we had discussed the nuclear disarmament problem with South Korea and not the United States, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula would not have ended at such a deadlock.”
However, the tone of Ri’s speech was completely different from that of last year when he told the United Nations General Assembly that an attack on the mainland of the United States with North Korean missiles was inevitable after Trump called Kim a “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim and his courage in taking disarmament measures at the United Nations, but said he still has a lot of work to do and that sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is nuclear-armed.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no timeline, saying: “It could take two years, three years, or five months - it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of Security Council sanctions must continue unabated until we recognize the full, definitive and verified state of nuclear disarmament.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously adopted additional sanctions on North Korea to cut off funding for North Korea's nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Rio on the sidelines of the United Nations General Assembly and later said Pyongyang would visit again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not end well.
When he left Pyongyang in July, he said progress had been made, and North Korea criticized him hours later for calling his demands “gangster-like.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to take down the missile testing station and nuclear test infrastructure if the United States takes “appropriate measures.”
Mr. Moon said Mr. Kim’s “appropriate measures” included security guarantees promised by Mr. Trump in Singapore and measures to normalise relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend a course to learn how to take enough time to rest
The goal of this year’s Harvard University course is to teach all undergraduates how to get more sleep. With such a course, they want to fight against the growing macho culture of “all-night” learning, where power accumulates with caffeine.
A university professor has found that students of the world’s best universities often don’t know the basics of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Women's Hospital, designed the course, which is after him the first of its kind in the United States.
He decided to conduct such a course after his lecture on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
At the end of the lecture, the girl approached him and said, “Why do I only find out now that I am in my senior year?”
She said no one had told her how important sleep was, and the professor told The Daily Telegraph that he was surprised.
The course, held for the first time this year, talks about the key importance of good sleeping habits for study and sports success, as well as for improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, says they opted for such a course when they found that students significantly lacked sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a student’s home door, where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports shoes, and books to get information about the impact of caffeine and light, the impact of lack of sleep on sports success, and the importance of a sleep routine.
In the second section, participants learn that prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart failure, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the student village with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We are aware that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know these facts, just as they have the right to know how cigarette smoking affects their health,” adds Professor Czeisler.
The professor says that the culture of pride is still present with “all-night learning”, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students, resulting in lack of sleep, present growing problems.
Professor Czeisler says that a sufficient amount of quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety. Thus, they can also avoid gaining weight - the brain goes into a mode of hunger due to lack of sleep, which makes students constantly hungry.
A 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology, Raymond So, helped Professor Czeisler design the course. Last year, during his first year at Harvard, he attended one of the professor’s lectures.
He says that the lecture opened his eyes and encouraged him to conduct a course throughout the student settlement.
He hopes that in the next stage, postgraduate students will be asked to complete a similar study programme before enrolling in a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set their alarm clock for sleep as well as waking up. He also wants to alert them to the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic displays and LED-lighting, as they can cause an imbalance of the circadian rhythm, making it difficult to fall asleep.
