Almanac: Inventor of the Geiger counter
We present a page from the almanac of our Sunday editions: on September 30, 1882, that is, on this day more than 136 years ago, Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany, who later became a world-famous physicist.
Geiger developed the method of detecting and measuring radioactivity, this invention was the basis for the development of a device called the Geiger counter.
It has become a fixture in the scientific world, and has also gained its place in pop culture, such as in the 1950 film Bells of Coronado, in which Roy Rogers and Dale Evans are played by cowboy scientists:
Man: “What the hell is that?”
Rogers: “It’s a Geiger counter. It’s used to look for radioactive minerals like uranium.
When you put on your headphones, you can hear the effect that radioactivity has on the atoms in the materials.”
“Oh my God, they’re really talking now!”
“Hans” Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
An invention with his name lives on.
