He said: “To date, these feelings of inferiority and difference are an actual thing that gives me the strength and persistence to achieve success.”
He wanted to prove that he was “something,” he said, not to disappoint anyone who would finally learn of his orientation.
The two-time bronze Olympic champion has become an influential advocate for LGBT rights and has appeared twice this year at the Commonwealth Games in Australia to urge countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said that he spoke because he felt happy, that he could speak openly without consequences, and that he wanted to give “hope” to others.
The three-time world champion said his romance with American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013, "surprised him."
Daley married an Oscar winner 20 years his senior last year, but he says the age difference was never a problem.
“When you’re that young,” he said, “it’s hard to find someone of the same age who would experience similar ups and downs.
The couple adopted their son, Robert Ray Black-Daley, in June, and Daley says it changed his “whole outlook.”
“If you asked me last year, all I would have to say is ‘I have to win a gold medal,’” he said.
But, you know, there are bigger things in the world than an Olympic gold medal.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie.
The son bears the same name as Daley's father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 from brain cancer.
