The four ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, commissioned in 2007, will replace the aging Bremen-class frigate class.
They are expected to have a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, and some cloaking technologies such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signature.
Other important features include longer maintenance intervals - the newest frigates could stay out of their home port for up to two years.
The continued delays mean that the top warships, which are supposed to allow Germany to exert its influence overseas, will be obsolete by the time they are deployed, notes the newspaper Die Ziet.
The unfortunate F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to take over the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned the ship to the shipyard after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, and the German media cited a number of key “programming and technical flaws” that would make the warship useless if it were sent on a combat mission.
The software flaws were particularly significant, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels would be manned by a crew of about 120 sailors - only half the workforce on the older Bremen-class frigates.
The ship was also found to be severely overweight, reducing its capacity and limiting the Navy's options for its future upgrade.
The 7000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz was said to be twice as heavy as the similar class of ships used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to the lack of equipment, the cost of the entire project - including the training of the crew - has become a problem.
It is expected to reach a staggering 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion) from an initial 2.2 billion euros.
Problems with the latest frigates are becoming particularly important in light of recent warnings that Germany’s naval power is shrinking.
