He regretted that no ships of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class could join the navy.
The National Trust eavesdrops on the secret lives of bats
A new study is under way on a property in the Highlands of Scotland to find out how bats use their diets to hunt for food.
They hope the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
In the study, scientists from the National Endowment for Scotland (NTS) will monitor small bats and tiny bats, as well as brown eared bats and bypass bats at the Inverewe Gardens estate in the Wester Ross area.
Special recorders will be set up at key locations of the estate to monitor bat activity throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile research using handheld detectors.
A professional sound analysis of all the recordings will confirm the frequency of calls from bats and what types of what they do.
They will then draw up a habitat map and report to create a detailed picture of their behaviour across the landscape.
Rob Dewar, an NTS nature conservation consultant, hopes the results will show which habitat areas are most suitable for bats and how each individual species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as the creation of grasslands and the conservation of forests for bats and other related species.
The number of bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom has declined sharply in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects shelters and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting, as well as flytraps and some types of chemical processing of building materials, as well as attacks of domestic cats, pose a risk.
Bats are not actually blind.
Night hunting habits, on the other hand, help you more with your ears than your eyes.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to accurately determine flight path errors and obstacles.
The NTS, which is responsible for supplying more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It employs ten experts who regularly carry out research, shelter checks and occasional rescues.
The organization even established the first and so far the only Scottish reserve specifically for bats at the Threevee estate in the Dumfries and Galloway area.
The estate manager, David Thompson, says the estate is their ideal territory.
“We have a great area for bats in Threave,” he said.
“We have old buildings, a lot of ancient trees and a whole quality habitat.
However, there is still a lot known about bats, so the work we do here and on other estates will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He stressed the importance of checking the presence of bats before carrying out maintenance work on the estates, as the possible inadvertent destruction of a single bat maternity hospital could result in the death of up to 400 females and pups, which could mean the collapse of the entire local population.
Bats are protected, so it is forbidden to kill, harass or disturb them, and it is also forbidden to destroy their maternity hospitals.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Fund, encouraged the public to participate.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and we just don’t know how well their populations hold up.”
